<TEXT>
the agriculture department is reviewing a grain 
companys possible links to a fugitive commodities trader in 
switzerland and its receipt of at least 65 million in government 
export subsidies 
at issue are the companys ties to marc rich who fled to 
switzerland in 1983 before his indictment for criminal tax evasion 
racketeering mail and wire fraud 
a department official confirmed tuesday that usda was examining 
richco grain ltd a swissbased company with an office in stamford 
conn and payments it received through the export enhancement 
program known as eep 
the review was started at the request of the chairman of a house 
agriculture subcommittee rep dan glickman dkan who raised 
questions about the company at a hearing earlier this year and on 
tuesday asked the agency for a full investigation 
glickman in a letter to the agency said an unmistakable line 
of ownership control and profit runs from richco grain to rich 
through a series of subsidiary arrangements 
while i am disturbed that a company whose main operations lie 
outside of the united states can establish but a nominal onshore 
presence and qualify to receive eep bonuses as appears to be the 
case with richco grain i am truly shocked that a fugitive from us 
justice can benefit from a program funded by taxpayer dollars 
glickman said in his letter to agriculture secretary clayton yeutter 
under the export enhancement program private exporters can sell 
us commodities at lower prices to meet foreign competition and 
then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities 
as bonuses or subsidies 
richard crowder under secretary for international affairs and 
