the government is not doing enough to keep the 
elderly from being ripped off by people appointed to handle their 
social security checks senators said after being told of abuses 
an arkansas woman and a california woman misused social security 
payments that they had been entrusted to manage on behalf of elderly 
beneficiaries the senate special committee on aging was told 
tuesday at a hearing 
elizabeth freeland of sacramento calif testified that she was 
told by the government that she needed a representative to handle 
her disability benefits because she was incapable of managing the 
money herself 
but she said the woman who was appointed kept some of the 
benefits for herself and had a history of writing bad checks she 
did not identify the appointee 
mary miller of marvell ark told the panel that her 
representative collected her disability benefits but then refused 
to use the money to buy a telephone clothes or other necessities 
that miller requested 
she often would not tell me how much money she would have of 
mine or what was going on she said 
the system is so ripe for abuse that in some communities in our 
nation private profiteers are virtually lining up at social 
security offices in the hope they can get their hands on a 
beneficiarys money by being appointed a payee said curtis child 
attorney for a legal services firm in sacramento 
he called the governments oversight of the payee program lax 
about 46 million social security beneficiaries have mental or 
physical impairments deemed serious enough that they need someone to 
manage their benefits 
the social security administration accepts applications from 
anyone who wants to be a payee but gives preference to relatives or 
to public or private groups with good records in handling elderly 
affairs 
but sens david pryor dark and john heinz rpa said the 
government has not been vigilant enough in overseeing the program 
there is some evidence that ssa has not been keeping a close 
watch on those who apply to be representative payees heinz said 
presently the ssa does not do background checks nor does the ssa 
monitor the program to ensure that the beneficiaries actually 
receive their money 
louis enoff an ssa deputy commissioner said the administration 
recognized there was a problem and was evaluating steps to remedy 
it he said the victims represent a small percentage of the 
beneficiarfies and are often poor or handicapped people without 
relatives to care for them 
enoff said ssa verifies the identities of payee applicants and 
asks them whether they have felony convictions 
he said he was concerned about a bill introduced by pryor and 
heinz on tuesday that would require ssa to conduct criminal 
background checks on applicants while barring most creditors from 
becoming payees 
a ban on creditors would be too stringent and would keep for 
example helpful landlords from becoming payees enoff said 
