<TEXT>
the chef of an exclusive french restaurant says 
veal producers who confine calves in small stalls and feed them 
noiron formula to get pure white meat have a mistaken idea of what 
the best cooks want 
as a chef the quality of the veal used in my kitchen is very 
important and yet of equal concern to me is the quality of life of 
these calves said jeanlouis palladin of jeanlouis restaurant at 
the watergate hotel in support of legislation that would change the 
way veal is raised 
palladin was one of 34 witnesses tuesday at a house agriculture 
subcommittee hearing in a debate over whether calves destined to 
become cuts of milkfed veal ought to spend their short lives in a 
freer state consuming more than just liquid 
the legislation pits animal rights advocates against government 
agriculture officials and most of the relatively small us veal 
industry 
palladin and others supporting the bill sponsored by rep charles 
bennett dfla said the rationale behind current practice is that 
the public wants pure white meat 
for me the foremost concern is the taste not the color of the 
meat said palladin he said he thinks the confinement of calves 
in small crates can lead to weakness illness and use of antibiotics 
in milk formulas all of which affect the quality of the meat 
but wanda cooper who has been raising calves in michigan since 
1976 said disease problems were nothing short of horrifying 
when she and her husband tried letting the animals roam 
we had no control over the amount of milk calves could drink at 
will weak calves were pushed aside navel sucking ear sucking and 
urine drinking were common she said 
dr john mcglone associate professor of animal science at texas 
tech university said there is no scientific evidence that solid 
food is better for calves than a milk formula with nutrients 
in answer to concerns about the lack of iron in calves diets 
mcglone said borderline anemia of veal calves does not cause 
serious health problems 
he said many of those attacking the industry actually have a 
broader goal of ending all human consumption of meat 
the veal industry is a small segment of american agriculture 
mcglone said because of its small size it is a relatively easy 
target for advocate roups that seek to reduce or eliminate use of 
animals by humans 
the bennett bill would require that calves be given solid food 
and iron have physical contact with one another and be kept in 
larger enclosures 
the crate system most commonly used in the united states is so 
confining that the calves cannot turn around or lie down 
comfortably said michael fox of the humane society of the united 
states 
these normally playful animals are kept practically immobile 
are prone to be unhealthy and lead a miserable existence said fox 
dr franklin loew dean of tufts university school veterinary 
medicine said veal stalls commonly are 22 to 24 inches wide and 60 
inches long he said calves average 239 pounds when they are 
slaughtered 
dr r d plowman administrator of the agriculture departments 
agricultural research service said about 1 million of the nearly 40 
million cattle slaughtered each year are specialfed calves at the 
center of this controversy 
there is a general perception that calves are purposely made 
iron deficient or anemic to produce the desired coloration of the 
meat said plowman this is not true 
he said research shows that raising calves in elevated 
individual stalls reduces disease and increases survival rates when 
calves nuzzle each other they pass along infections he said 
