<TEXT>
more proof of the danger is needed before 
governments launch programs seeking to correct the greenhouse 
warming of the planet a pair of scientists is cautioning 
there does seem to have been a warming over the last 100 years 
but too much uncertainty remains about the causes of that change to 
justify immediate government action said robert jastrow former 
head of nasas goddard institute for space studies 
the effect of clouds is not well understood and the small 
warming recorded so far could easily be a result of normal climate 
variability or changes in the brightness of the sun explained the 
former national aeronautics and space administration scientist 
current forecasts of the manmade greenhouse effect do not 
appear to be sufficiently accurate to be used as a basis for sound 
national policy decisions said jastrow 
jastrow made his comments in releasing the study scientific 
perspectives on the greenhouse problem the report was presented 
by jastrow and frederick seitz a former president of the national 
science foundation and of rockefeller university a third coauthor 
william a nierenberg of the scripps institute of oceanography 
could not attend the news conference on tuesday 
the study was published by the george c marshall institute in 
washington the institute funded by foundation grants conducts 
research on public policy issues said jastrow 
in recent years the threat of greenhouse warming has attracted 
considerable attention with some scientists warning that it could 
raise the earths temperature changing the climate turning major 
farm areas into dust bowls and melting the polar ice caps causing a 
rise in sea levels 
the warming would result from increases in gases such as carbon 
dioxide and methane in the atmosphere these gases allow warmth from 
the sun to pass through to the earth but block outgoing radiation 
raising the planets temperature in somewhat the same way a 
greenhouse warms its interior 
james hansen jastrows successor at goddard has been a leader 
in this research warning that the effect may already be observable 
in studies indicating the planet is about 1 degree fahrenheit warmer 
now than it was a century ago 
that conclusion has been widely debated with various climate 
experts differing on the effect of clouds urban growth and other 
factors in changing average temperatures 
we dont believe he has overstated the risks of this 
warming commented jastrow of hansens work 
but jastrow added the one place we part company is the 
ability to forecast the next century from what we know now 
jastrow recommended increased research spending to determine the 
extent of the danger if any 
research facilities costing 100 million or so could help provide 
these answers in three to five years he said still plenty of time 
to act if it is found that a gloabl warming is indeed underway 
