<TEXT>
the government said today that savings and loan 
customers withdrew 54 billion from their accounts in april a high 
number but an improvement compared with the record outflows earlier 
in the year 
it was the 12th consecutive month of withdrawals and the sixth in 
a row when outflows exceeded 5 billion according to a report by 
the federal home loan bank board which regulates the nations 2934 
sampls 
in the first four months of the year customers withdrew 337 
billion more than they deposited compared with a 162 billion gain 
in deposits during the same period of last year 
withdrawals set a onemonth record of 108 billion in january 
slipping to 92 billion in february and 83 billion in march 
james barth chief economist of the bank board said the april 
figure is better than it at first appears 
about half of the outflow is accounted for by 10 thrifts four 
of which are insolvent he said in a statement the deposit 
outflow figures are even smaller when you account for seasonal 
factors since one of the poorest deposit flow months of the year is 
april when people are paying income taxes 
on a seasonally adjusted basis the outflow was 16 billion 
down sharply from 67 billion in march and the smallest outflow 
since last september 
barth attributed the continuing withdrawals to the failure of 
sampls to keep pace with rising interest rates offered by competitors 
such as mutual funds and to orders from regulators requiring 
overextended thrift institutions to shrink 
private analysts say lack of public confidence in sampls is also a 
factor to remedy that the bush administration has urged congress 
to move more swiftly on its bailout plan now not expected to reach 
the presidents desk until next month 
