<TEXT>
solidarity plans to support progressive 
communist candidates in the june 18 runoff elections to build on its 
already stunning success in parliamentary elections spokesmen said 
wednesday 
communist officials stung by their widespread rejection in 
polands freest elections since 1947 have been pushing solidarity 
to join some sort of governing coalition with the party 
the independent trade union has so far refused saying it prefers 
to keep its freedom to criticize government policies but its 
electoral dominance has severely undermined the authority of the 
communists and left questions about their ability to govern 
the murky political situation following sundays election was 
expected to be the no 1 topic thursday when representatives of the 
two sides led by solidarity leader lech walesa and interior 
minister czeslaw kiszczak meet in warsaw 
official voting results were expected to be issued either 
wednesday night or thursday according to the official news agency 
pap the party has already conceded a decided defeat 
solidarity was limited by a political deal it struck with 
authorities in april to run for only 35 percent or 161 of the 460 
seats in the sejm the lower chamber of parliament 
solidarity says it already has won 160 of those seats and that 
the remaining seat should be sealed up in the june 18 runoffs for 
candidates who failed to win 50 percent of the vote the union said 
but in most cases the candidates of the communist party and its 
allies who ran for the remaining 299 sejm seats did not obtain the 
requisite 50 percent in the first round of voting and will have to 
participate in the second round 
this gives solidarity the opportunity to choose among the 
communist and allied candidates those who most nearly agree with 
solidaritys program 
our opinion is that it is worthwhile to get engaged in the 
second round in order to present to our voters candidates who in 
out estimation are better candidates warsaw campaign chief jan 
litynski told a news conference in the capital 
we want to give all the candidates a chance to present their 
platforms to our voters and we will probably arrange meetings to 
discuss qualifications of the official sides candidates he said 
the meetings would be between the already elected solidarity 
deputies and those hopefuls still in the running for the communist 
party or the allied peasant and democratic party seats he said 
litynski noted that in sundays elections some communistbacked 
candidates already had shown they were more popular with voters than 
others and that solidarity would help make such people more widely 
known 
endorsement by solidarity was virtually tantamount to being 
elected in the first round if the same holds true june 18 
solidarity could be able to determine nearly the entire makeup of 
the sejm 
according to its unofficial tally solidarity already has won 92 
of the possible 100 senate seats and its candidates who must enter 
the runoffs generally were the highest vote getters in their 
districts after the runoffs it appeared possible the union would 
hold all 100 seats 
still undecided is what to do about the 35 seats reserved for 
prominent communist and government officials who were allowed to run 
opposed all the candidates had to do was win 50 percent of the 
vote but voters reportedly have overwhelmingly rejected them 
litynski and national solidarity spokesman janusz onyszkiewicz 
shed little light at the news conference on the progress of talks to 
determine how to fill those seats that are expected to be vacant 
according to solidarity among the defeated is prime minister 
mieczyslaw f rakowski interior minister czeslaw kiszczak and six 
other members on the ruling 17member politburo 
solidarity has promised to allow the party to fill the seats even 
though its candidates were defeated under the april accord that 
made the elections possible and resulted in solidaritys 
legalization solidarity ceded 65 percent of the sejm to the 
communists and their affiliated groups 
solidarity and government representatives held informal talks 
tuesday on the issue but nothing was resolved and the union says it 
still awaits the governments proposed solutions 
onyszkiewicz said kiszczak and walesa would discuss it further at 
thursdays full meeting of the arbitration commission a panel set 
up to resolve any conflicts between the government and opposition 
stemming from their historic accord that liberalized polands 
election process 
we will learn there what are the possibilities for solving this 
problem onyszkiewicz said 
