<TEXT>
the nations governors urged congress wednesday 
to try anew to forge a longterm national energy policy and said it 
should include tax and price incentives for the development of 
domestic resources even in currently restricted wilderness and 
offshore areas 
democratic gov steve cowper of alaska presenting 
recommendations of the national governors association after an 
18month study declared the nation simply may not be able to 
afford to permanently remove prospectively valuable oil and gas 
areas off its shores in vast areas of the west and in the arctic 
as a personal note he added it is my belief that we 
cannot afford to foreclose development in the arctic national 
wildlife refuge even in the wake of the environmental furor over 
the damage caused by the massive spill of the exxon valdez oil 
tanker any development in currently restricted areas can and must 
comply with the strictest environmental safeguards including 
standards for tanker safety he said 
cowper noted the governors also recommended the export of alaskan 
oil on a barrelforbarrel trade basis with other nations he said 
the current prohibition against such exports reflects the 
political situation at the time the alaska pipeline legislation was 
passed not the real workings of the oil markets or the economic 
realities of oil trade 
i am convinced that such trades would be economically 
beneficial given the high transport cost of moving alaskan oil to 
gulf coast refineries where much of it goes today cowper told 
the house banking subcommittee on economic stabilization the 
nation would not lose oil supplies as the result of these 
transactions 
cowper who was joined by representatives of the governors of 
pennsylvania oklahoma new york and montana acknowledged that 
energy issues are not a central concern to most people today 
despite memories of the oil shocks of the 1970s however he 
said i come before you to say that complacency is both 
unwarranted and dangerous 
the trends are in the wrong direction he said domestic 
oil production is down oil production in other stable and 
friendly nations is down as a percentage of world oil production 
the concentration of oil productive capacity in the persian gulf is 
up and domestic oil consumption is up in the transportation sector 
alone the nation now uses more oil than it produces 
cowper noted the united states imported more than 43 percent of 
the oil it consumed last year and the bill accounted for more than 
onefourth of the us trade deficit what is more he said 
after nearly 15 years of improvement in our efficiency of energy 
use the most recent figures from the department of energy indicate 
that our energy efficiency has started to decline we use twice as 
much energy per unit of gnp as japan and nearly twice that of our 
european trading partners 
he said the governors want congress to take a hard look at a 
variety of incentives for domestic oil and gas exploration and for 
coal including standard investment tax credits on exploration and 
the deregulation of natural gas wellhead prices 
in 1977 congress passed a law requiring the president to develop 
and send to the senate and house comprehensive 5 and 10year energy 
plans and to update them every two years 
despite that law said rep mary rose oakar dohio head of the 
subcommittee this country has no national energy policy plan 
worthy of the name the last plan submitted by president reagan 
in 1986 totaled a mere two pages she pointed out 
ms oakar said the nation has been asleep on energy security 
for the past eight years and that is why the alaska oil spill was a 
wakeup call for america 
