<TEXT>
as many as 14 million american children suffer 
from some mental disorder a problem that is costing society 
billions of dollars and depriving the nation of productive citizens 
according to a study released wednesday 
there is a stigma associated with mental illness and there is a 
major problem in how childrens problems are perceived said james 
f leckman of yale university the chairman of an institute of 
medicine committee that prepared the study 
mentally ill children have historically been underserved he 
said noting that this is a clear and persistent problem in our 
society 
although the committee said millions of youngsters are not 
receiving the mental therapy they need leckman said the study was 
an optimistic report because the last two decades have witnessed 
breakthroughs in understanding preventing and correcting many 
childhood mental diseases 
the committee recommended that the national institute of mental 
health be given annual budget increases to develop research and to 
train professionals to deal with the specific mental illnesses of 
those under 18 
we must examine our priorities as a nation to ensure that 
these real and persistent problems no longer place in jeopardy our 
most valuable resource future generations of productive 
citizens leckman said 
the report said that a conservative estimate says 12 percent of 
americas children are mentally disturbed but that the true number 
could be as high as 22 percent or about 14 million 
leckman added the likelihood is that the rate is increasing 
of the mentally ill members of the committee said only 20 
percent to 33 percent receive care some studies the experts said 
say the majority of mentally ill children are never even diagnosed 
by parents teachers and doctors 
for the physically handicapped the evidence is that 80 percent 
of those are served said dr fredric solomon director of the 
mental health division of the institute of medicine yet for 
serious emotional disturbance the evidence is that less than 30 and 
maybe less than 20 percent are served even when they are noticed 
solomon said studies have shown that even medical professionals 
such as pediatricians generally recognize only about about 
onefourth of their patients who are suffering from mental 
disorders he said often the children who receive attention are 
those with disruptive behavior 
dr glen r elliott vice chairman of the committee and a 
professor of psychiatry at the university of california san 
francisco said studies have shown a definite increase in childhood 
suicides and in eating disorders 
the report identified a variety of problems besetting americas 
children these include developmental impairments that slow 
education and learning emotional disturbances that include anxiety 
depression or both and behavioral problems that include disruptive 
and antisocial acts 
some of those problems manifest themselves as chronic drug use 
sexual problems and eating disorders 
poverty and associated harsh childraising methods contribute 
heavily to the number of troubled youth the experts said the 
report noted that youngsters with mental and behavioral problems 
may exceed 20 percent in some populations such as innercity 
children who are exposed to severe psychological adversity 
the total cost to the nation has not been measured but leckman 
said it is enormous 
billions of dollars are spent each year in direct service 
delivery said leckman added to this is the tremendous 
emotional burden carried by their families 
childhood depression left untreated may lead to suicide he 
said some disorders such as autism may be a lifelong disability 
other mental problems may lead to drug abuse and criminal behavior 
despite the distress and misery and great costs to society 
relatively few resources have been directed at efforts to advance 
our knowledge said leckman 
the committee said that the nation needs to invest in fundamental 
research to learn how to treat such children and to train 
specialists who can conduct research and treatment 
there are fewer than 100 child psychiatrists who devote 30 
percent of their time to research leckman said the figures are 
equally dismal in psychology pediatrics social work and special 
education 
the committee recommended a nationwide plan directed by the 
national institute of mental health to nurture careers in childhood 
mental health and to sponsor research into methods of preventing 
detecting and treating mental illness in children the report called 
for a national investment that would grow to 198 million annually 
by the fifth year 
the institute of medicine is part of the national academy of 
sciences a private organization chartered by congress as an adviser 
to the federal government in scientific and technical matters 
</TEXT>
