<TEXT>
kathy wilhelm has reported for the associated 
press from beijing since 1987 she lives next to the foreign 
compound that was fired at by troops early wednesday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
i woke to gunfire wednesday morning 
i almost rolled over and went back to sleep the sound of guns 
has become routine since hundreds of thousands of soldiers rolled 
into downtown beijing last weekend and drove student protesters from 
tiananmen square 
instead i dashed to a window that overlooks changan avenue 
beijings main eastwest street where dozens of tanks and trucks of 
troops were parked two blocks west of my apartment 
peering over the sill i could see no violence only a few dozen 
chinese bicycling under a grim gray sky skirting torn up road 
dividers 
but the import of the shots became clear later chinese 
authorities claimed someone had fired on the troops marching along 
changan avenue from a foreigners apartment in the compound next to 
mine 
dozens of soldiers took up positions outside the compound 
pointing their rifles at the buildings some fired at the buildings 
reportedly knocking out windows dozens more closed the compound 
gates while plainclothes officials searched inside 
eerily a loudspeaker on an army vehicle began playing gentle 
music 
do they want to fight or do they want to dance asked a 
chinese employee watching from a stairwell in the compound 
the simple act of closing the compound gates touched off panic in 
the foreign community those locked inside gathered to plead with 
the impassive soldiers to be let out 
i have a plane ticket and they wont let me out to catch the 
plane said a european diplomat a soviet reporter pleaded in vain 
for permission to evacuate five children 
a long line of cars from various embassies formed outside 
after two hours plainclothes officials collared a chinese man 
who they said fired at the troops and brought him out to the 
soldiers abruptly they formed lines and trotted off 
the gates opened and hundreds of residents rushed to cars and 
vans some bound for the airport and some for hotels further from 
the troop positions 
all but a small group of residents also left the compound where 
the associated press has its office and several staff apartments 
yes we are brave boasted a bulgarian diplomat who stayed 
behind a bulgarian woman living two floors down from him opened her 
door only after much persuasion and perspired with anxiety 
be careful its not safe out there anywhere she urged 
more shops were open wednesday than earlier in the crackdown but 
business was slow far fewer vendors appeared with fruits and 
vegetables 
i loaded as much as i could into my knapsack and bicycle basket 
eggplant and stringbeans were available tuesday but only cabbages 
and tomatoes were in the shops on wednesday prices were heavily 
inflated cutting into my dwindling cash supply banks are closed 
the government warned that water and electricty might be cut if 
order is not restored and i went home and filled jars and buckets 
with water 
gas stations closed early in the turmoil the driver of one of 
the few taxis still operating said he was charging a minumum of 50 
for the airport trip usually a 9 fare he talked one desperate 
passenger into paying 1000 he said 
the international hotel sent guests a cheery letter wednesday 
inviting them to a cocktail party with the management and hoping 
their stay would be memorable but a second letter warned 
stay off the balconies and keep your heavy curtains closed 
away from the foreign neighborhood the mood of panic eased most 
chinese were too nervous to travel to work but they relaxed within 
their walled stone homes in the narrow alleyways 
old men played chinese chess on a canal bank oblivious to 
rifletoting soldiers who roamed a nearby alley in groups of two and 
three 
one man called out to me have you been shot at yet 
two colleagues were ap reporter terrill jones said nonuniformed 
security forces marching in formation down changan avenue shot at 
him twice as he stood outside the international hotel taking 
photographs he fled to the hotel entrance only to find the door 
boarded from the inside 
ap reporter dan biers was on changan further east when an army 
truck approached from the north with soldiers firing out the rear 
he took shelter behind a tree 
