<TEXT>
a 1978 agreement requiring the navy to buy 
cruisemissile engines from a defense contractor in michigan is 
illegal and will be canceled the navy has told a senator in a 
letter made public wednesday 
according to the letter dated april 11 from thennavy 
undersecretary h lawrence garrett iii to sen carl levin dmich 
the openended multimilliondollar agreement with williams 
international of walled lake mich was negotiated by william 
parkin 
parkin a consultant and a former navy employee and the former 
navy engineer he bribed were given 26month prison terms june 2 for 
illegally scheming to help two companies get pentagon contracts 
parkin and stuart berlin were each fined 25000 and ordered to 
serve two years of supervised probation after their release from 
prison parkin pleaded guilty to charges that he bribed berlin to 
provide secret navy bid information that would help teledyne 
industries inc and hazeltine corp of long island ny obtain 
lucrative contracts to sell electronic equipment to the pentagon 
the garrett letter to levin was made public by the project on 
military procurement a washingtonbased whistleblower group 
danielle brianbland a spokeswoman for the group declined to say 
how the letter was obtained 
the associated press sought comment from the navy on the 
agreement the navys press office said it was unable to provide 
information immediately both the navy and levins office confirmed 
the existence of the garrett letter 
the agreement guarantees williams a certain level of engine sales 
to the navy without the agreement williams would be required to 
compete for contracts with teledyne industries inc the other 
supplier of the engines williams is fighting the navys decision 
williams and the navy negotiated the agreement in order to 
provide the defense department with a second source for cruise 
missiles said linda gustitus staff director of the senate 
subcommittee on oversight of government operations which levin 
heads 
williams licensed some of its technology to teledyne and in 
return the defense department agreed to buy at least 240 engines a 
year from williams plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up 
to 1200 engines annually 
the agreement contains no ending date and purports to apply not 
just to the contract with which its negotiation was associated but 
to all government contracts for f107 engines its derivatives and 
associated logistic items having cruisemissile applications 
wrote garrett who is now secretary of the navy 
the navy under the agreement must contract through williams in 
buying engines from teledyne williams has been paid about 36000 
for each of the 708 engines built by teledyne garrett wrote 
such provisions violate a 1984 amendment to defense purchasing 
legislation designed to ensure competition in pentagon procurement 
because it binds the government to reward future contracts garrett 
wrote levin was an author of the amendment 
in a may 12 letter made public by levin a navy contracting 
officer frances l bradley told williams the agreement wasnt 
authorized by purchasing laws in effect when the deal was negotiated 
the f107 engine is used in seabased tomahawk cruise missiles 
the government ought to keep its word levin said wednesday 
the government made a contract and under the constitution you 
cannot abrogate a contract 
the 1984 law applies only to new agreements not to existing 
ones and so the agreement with williams is within the law levin 
said i dont concede in any way the 1984 law was violated by the 
contract even if it came after the 1984 law levin said 
williams vice president for public relations david jolivette 
declined to discuss the issue on the advice of counsel saying the 
matter had not yet been resolved 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

