<TEXT>
members of a house panel on aging said 
wednesday the federal government should do more to help states 
combat the growing problem of abuse and neglect of the elderly 
how much abuse there is cannot be documented but only a fraction 
of the cases are reported to state authorities the panel was told 
members want to see the national government play a more active 
role rep tom downey dny told michio suzuki acting deputy 
commissioner of the administration on aging in the department of 
health and human services at a house subcommittee hearing 
downey chairman of the human services subcommittee of the house 
select committee on aging acknowledged that the federal effort has 
been hamstrung by lack of public awareness of the problem and cuts 
in available funds funding cutbacks but he said were prepared 
to give you more resources 
rep louise slaughter dny questioned how suzukis agency 
could address the problem without a clear picture of its national 
scope and added im not sure a federal passive role is going to 
help 
suzuki rejected the description of his agency as passive he 
said the office plays an active role in a supporting role by 
providing assistance to states 
the administration on aging has long recognized that prevention 
of elder abuse is primarily a state responsibility and a state 
prerogative he told the panel 
but downey and other members noted that the federal government 
has made many efforts to take the lead in fighting child abuse 
including monitoring state activities 
it seems to me that what would be of national interest in the 
younger years of life would be of national concern in the older 
years of life he said 
suzuki said the federal agency has not evaluated individual state 
efforts to prevent abuse and neglect of older americans but is 
trying to be responsive to states needs in developing programs 
supplying educational materials and enhancing public awareness 
though states are not required to spend any of the money they get 
from the agency on protective services 40 states do allocate some 
of their federal funds to these services he said 
states are as interested in this as we are he said 
suzuki said his agency relies on the national aging resource 
center on elder abuse to gather information on the scope of the 
problem and the efforts of the states the center operated by the 
american public welfare association the national association of 
state units on aging and the university of delaware receives 
federal funds 
toshio tatara director of the center testified that because the 
reporting systems in many states are incomplete it is impossible to 
estimate accurately the extent of the problem 
he said state surveys turned up 140000 reports of abuse of the 
elderly last year but he said that represents only a fraction of 
the incidents 
one study found that only one of 14 cases gets reported which 
would mean that last year there would have been nearly 2 million 
reportable cases he said 
elder abuse is far less likely to be reported than child abuse 
about which the public has gained greater awareness of the problem 
than it has about elder abuse he said 
tatara called for better coordination of federal programs and 
regulations 
as an example he cited a federal medicare and medicaid policy 
that he said contributes to patient neglect under that policy 
the cost of a medical device that prevents bed sores is not covered 
though the cost of treating bed sores is he said 
