congressional investigators said wednesday that 
the air force is relying on outside consultants rather than its own 
personnel to determine the cost of the 68 billion system of 
railgarrison mx missiles 
officials from the general accounting office an investigating 
arm of congress told a house panel that the army navy and air 
force use consultants for a wide range of services 
the total number however is likely higher than the agency found 
because the definition of consultant varies and many contractors do 
not report whether consultants worked on certain programs 
investigators said 
the house armed services subcommittee on investigations 
responding to last summers operation ill wind investigation of 
military purchasing fraud had asked the agency to look into the 
pentagons use of consultants 
the gao studied one weapon system from each of the three services 
the armys 32 billion fiber optic guided missile program the 
navys v22 osprey a 26 billion tiltrotor aircraft program and 
the air forces system to deploy the landbased nuclear mx missile 
on railroad cars 
the ballistic systems division which manages the mx program 
awarded 15 contracts worth about 99 million for support services 
during fiscal 1987 and 1988 said harold j johnson director of 
manpower issues in the gao national security and international 
affairs division 
the support contractors provided cost estimates reviews of 
contractor logistic support plans and helped determine system and 
component specifications 
the gao report prompted rep nicholas mavroules dmass 
chairman of the subcommittee to question who estimates the cost of 
the mx railgarrison the air force or the consultants hired by the 
service 
