the senate narrowly rejected a proposal 
wednesday to delay the start of major provisions of medicares new 
catastrophic health care coverage a proposal opponents argued would 
have effectively killed the new benefits 
reacting to criticism from senior citizens opposed to paying an 
income tax surcharge to help pay for the program backers of the 
delay proposal argued that it was unfair to put roughly twothirds 
of the cost of the program on roughly onethird of retired americans 
with enough income to make them subject to income taxes 
those who voted against delaying the coverage maintained that 
huge federal budget deficits make it impossible to provide new 
benefits without providing a way to pay for them and that middleand 
upperincome retired americans should foot a major share of the cost 
the surtax could be as much as 800 a year for medicareeligible 
retirees in upper income ranges 
in the key vote the senate voted 5149 against an attempt by 
sen john mccain rariz to kill an amendment by senate majority 
leader george mitchell of maine that called on the finance committee 
to review the program while benefits continue on schedule mitchell 
introduced his amendment as a substitute to mccains proposal to 
delay provisions while a way to reduce the surtax is found 
the senate then quickly adopted by voice votes the mitchell 
substitute amendment and attached it to a pending supplemental 
appropriations measure to pump 33 billion additional money into a 
variety of federal programs for the current fiscal year 
nowhere in my amendment will you find the word repeal but you 
will find the word delay mccain maintained he termed the 
mitchell amendment a smokescreen that would not require finance 
