<TEXT>
construction unions and businesses have agreed 
to a plan that would keep heavy trucks from making deliveries during 
peak commuting hours to help reduce air pollution mayor tom bradley 
announced tuesday 
southern californias skies are among the nations most polluted 
because of surrounding mountains that trap the filth along with 
stagnant weather and industries that operate in the area 
the city agreed to exempt from its proposed traffic management 
program trucks and equipment necessary for pouring concrete laying 
hot asphalt and erecting structural steel bradley said 
in return the construction industry agreed to shift its work 
hours without premium pay to 6 am to 3 pm instead of the 
current 7 am to 4 pm to reduce truck and automobile traffic 
bradley said 
the onehour shift would remove about 125000 construction 
workers from city streets during morning and afternoon rushhour 
traffic the mayor said 
the proposal developed by the city jointly with a regional air 
quality control agency would require truck operators to pay a 
surcharge for a license allowing them to use city streets during 
rush hour it also would create a rapid deployment task force 
intended to quickly respond and clean up major accidents 
the altered work schedule would involve members of 83 union 
locals including boiler makers brick layers carpenters operating 
engineers teamsters general contractors pipe trade workers and 
painters 
the plan is expected to go before the city council early next 
month 
