<DOCNO> AP890607-0202 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
why use a cudgel when a scalpel is called for 
in one form or another that question forever arises in 
discussions of federal reserve or monetary policy which involves 
decisions about the supply and cost of money in the economy 
most likely it will continue to arise for years to come the 
simple truth being that monetary officials are familiar with the 
cudgel a blunt instrument but havent yet acquired skill with the 
more refined scalpel 
as a consequence critics say the feds inevitable first 
reaction to signs of inflation is to slow the economy mainly by 
restricting the money supply and thereby raising interest rates 
it works just as a human being would falter under repeated blows 
to the head the economy eventually slows factories close 
unemployment rises and demand lessens no mystery there people just 
dont have the money to buy 
but the question remains why should the fed have to slow the 
whole economy rather than simply restraining the inflationary 
culprits because the instruments and skills dont seem to be 
available to it 
john wright an international investment adviser and frequent 
critic of fed policy claims that for years monetary policy failed 
to perceive the true causes of domestic inflation and needlessly 
bludgeoned the american economy 
he becomes particularly incensed at repeated federal reserve 
efforts to dampen the american economy because of a factor that 
should have been dealt with abroad the inflationary factor was 
eurodollars created by european banks 
in his view these dollars created whenever dollardenominated 
loans were made by foreign banks created a classic inflation 
scenario that of too many dollars chasing too few goods 
prices rose but not because of domestic demand but because 
foreign banks created dollars without any supervision or restraints 
by american authorities 
still he says the fed response to eurodollar inflation was to 
cudgel the american economy into repeated recessions 
a somewhat similar worry arises today inflation for the 12 
months ended in april was 51 percent up from 39 percent in the 
year before as measured by the consumer price index the suggestion 
is that of general inflation 
however over the same time the consumer price index inflation 
rate for all items less food and energy barely rose for the 12 
months ended in april 1988 it was 43 percent for the 12 months 
through april 1989 it was 46 percent 
exclude food and energy prices and the inflation rate is almost 
stable add them and you have a dangerous trend now however there 
are some indications that food and energy prices may have 
stabilized albeit at high levels 
last years drought largely was responsible for driving up food 
prices by 65 percent while there is no assurance the drought will 
not continue or resume those knowledgeable about weather conditions 
are optimistic 
last year energy prices rose 87 percent largely on the basis of 
reduced production by members of the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries this year there are some indications supplies 
will be larger than before 
fed watchers therefore are expressing optimism that fed policy 
wont grow harsher and even that the fed will ease up on the 
economy allowing interest rates to fall 
in short the belief is that the fed will try to use the scalpel 
instead of the familiar cudgel 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0203 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
often derided as a nice place to live but you 
wouldnt want to visit atlanta tries one more time next month to 
amuse conventioneers and capture its soul as underground atlanta 
opens for business again 
seven years after the lights went out ostensibly for good the 
entertainment and shopping playground beneath downtown is set to 
open thursday after a threeyear overhaul under the auspices of the 
rouse co the wizards of american urban reclamation 
in its prime underground atlanta was atlantas answer to the 
french quarter created in old storefronts that were the citys 
heart before a network of bridges over railroad tracks literally 
raised downtown one level 
underground had swinging dixieland loud rock n roll cool 
jazz fine eateries chic watering holes even a shop where 
segregationist restaurateurturnedgovernor lester maddox signed 
autographs and sold souvenirs 
underground opened in 1969 peaked in 1972 was struggling by 
1975 and was gone by 1982 it was eulogized as the victim of crime 
or a perception thereof derelicts subway construction ripoff 
merchants and changing times there were dozens of theories about 
what went wrong but seemingly no answers 
without it downtown atlanta has acquired the reputation of a 
ghost town after dark which has been an albatross around the neck 
of the citys thriving convention industry while conventioneers sit 
in gleaming downtown hotels real atlantans are miles away in the 
biracial citys largely white suburbs 
in 1985 the city signed the deal for a 142 million 
rerevitalization it turned to rouse the people responsible for 
bostons faneuil hall market place baltimores harborplace new 
yorks south street seaport among other projects 
were trying to create a town center for metropolitan atlanta 
back to the birthplace of atlanta said joseph g martin jr 
president of the underground atlanta development company we want 
it to be a place where visitors will come to find out about what 
atlanta has to offer but where also the hometown crowd can feel 
some sense of identity 
mayor andrew young sees the new underground as one of the most 
significant accomplishments of two terms in office this 
represents a new heart for atlanta it represents a gathering place 
for the entire metro area 
the new underground is on and around the original site on 
downtowns south side just blocks from the highrise hotel 
district its three times the size of the old underground visitors 
will find 22 restaurants and nightclubs and nearly 100 retailers 
while the emphasis on retailing marks a change for underground the 
entertainment focus is something new for rouse 
weve never done this strong an entertainment aspect to any of 
our urban places said william m coleman vice president and 
general manager of rouseatlanta the rouse affiliate created to run 
the project 
some of that is due to the name he said underground 
atlanta has probably the highest name recognition of any project 
weve ever touched and what underground atlanta was known for 
was entertainment 
rouse officials anticipate 10 million to 11 million visitors a 
year half of them outoftowners they say there are enough office 
workers and conventiongoers downtown to meet threefourths of 
undergrounds needs 
even so martin said the real test of whether the project 
succeeds is whether the project appeals to residents the 
obvious concern what a lot of people talk about around here is 
security 
thats because the old underground came to be regarded as 
dangerous 
dante stephensen whose dantes down the hatch jazz club and 
restaurant anchored the old underground said at its worst 
underground had a lower crime rate than lenox square a popular 
mall but downtown areas cant protect themselves from bad 
publicity 
clearly this time around underground must be perceived as safe 
weve taken a commonsense approach martin said a squad of 
some 30 private guards will patrol accompanied by atlanta police 
who are building a 34officer substation there planners have made 
sure there are no blind alleys and lighting designers have made it 
bright enough to read at midnight 
martin admits to being irked that he is repeatedly asked what 
underground will do to keep out undesirables first tell me 
who the undesirables are this is a town center its open to 
everyone if a person comes to underground and happens to look 
different thats fine if a person starts to infringe on somebody 
elses rights thats not fine 
a nononsense security policy seems to have wide public appeal 
where city officials triggered a storm of criticism with a plan to 
run vagrants out before last years democratic national convention 
hardly anything has been heard from anyone concerned about 
loiterers civil rights in underground 
i dont see it as a problem coleman said the biggest 
problem is in perception and that perception problem goes away as 
people come here and have a good time and find out they arent 
hassled 
i would be surprised martin said if underground is not 
the safest place in the whole atlanta area 
it had better be the city has sunk more than 80 million in 
revenue bonds as well as other public funding into underground if 
it flops the city could be forced to cough up some 3 million a 
year for 30 years 
underground is important symbolically and it is a test of 
whether a town center can work here whether we have enough 
cohesiveness martin said because if we continue to drift 
apart as weve been doing there could be all sorts of consequences 
economic political social and otherwise 
and although rouse has relatively little capital invested the 
companys track record is on the line it seems that each year 
the expectations get higher as they see whats happened in other 
cities coleman said 
rouse has taken slums and turned them into landmarks said 
stephenson who is reopening dantes and underground atlanta was 
never as bad at its worst as any of those other areas were 
project officials maintain theres virtually no way underground 
will fail 
im convinced underground is going to be a great success 
martin said pointing out that while two developers put together the 
first underground on a shoestring this time the city is landlord 
partner and major investor 
the city leaders recognize how important it is and theyre not 
going to let it fail he said they just cant 
