<DOCNO> AP890607-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
as interest rates drop smart homeowners with 
variable rate mortgages are preparing for a great leap forward by 
voluntarily raising their monthly payments 
such homeowners and there are lots of them exploit the cyclical 
nature of interest rates by accelerating their payments when rates 
are down and slowing them when rates rise thus obtaining the 
greatest return for their dollar 
not everyone has the cash flow to do so of course but even 
small amounts can make a big difference when repeated for many 
months 
assuming a fiveyear cycle of high and low rates some of these 
homeowners add to their payments for the 30 months or so when rates 
are lowest and then add nothing to their payments during the high 
end of the cycle 
in such ways they can pare years from the maturity date of their 
loans 
the theory is similar to what is practiced regularly in the stock 
market where wise investors buy when stock prices are low and avoid 
further commitments when prices are high thus getting the most 
shares for the dollar 
in real estate homeowners in effect obtain more equity for the 
dollar by adding to their payments when their variable mortgage 
rates fall in effect such prepayments 
buy more equity for the buck 
accelerate the equityloan ratio or the amount of the monthly 
payment that goes to equity versus loan repayment 
most of the payment in the first few months of a mortgage loan is 
to repay interest as each month passes more money is applied to 
equity and less to interest until near maturity the payments are 
almost all equity 
by making additional payments that process is hastened not only 
does the additional payment in itself lower the loan amount and 
add to the equity but it jumps the homeowner into the more 
favorable equityloan relationship 
shrink the mortgage maturity date perhaps for example from 
20 years to 18 saving thousands of dollars of interest payments 
all three of these benefits are simply different ways of saying 
the same thing that when you speed up repayments especially when 
rates are at the low point in the cycle you can save substantial 
sums 
unless drastic changes occur in the way the american economy 
operates such opportunities will present themselves at least two or 
three times in a 20year period economies are cyclical forever 
expanding or contracting 
during the old days of fixedrate mortgages homeowners didnt 
have the opportunity to take advantage of these cycles no matter 
what happened to rates in general borrowers were locked into their 
initial contract rates 
variable rates were developed primarily because lenders wanted 
them for their own protection why they reasoned should they be 
locked into low rates for long terms when their own costs of 
obtaining money might rise 
lenders thus obtained the protection they sought but in so doing 
they also left an opening for savvy homeowners 
there is nothing in most mortgage contracts written today to 
prevent borrowers from taking advantage of the low end of the 
interestrate cycle 
even for bankers it seems security comes at a price 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0210 </DOCNO>
