<TEXT>
opec oil ministers today reached a 
tentative agreement to raise their production a modest amount to 
keep prices strong in the coming months 
the ministers of the 13nation organization of petroleum 
exporting countries held a flurry of meetings to try to wrap up an 
agreement 
venezuelan oil minister celestino armas asked if a deal had been 
struck replid yes of course 
saudi arabias hisham nazer said the new production ceiling would 
be 195 million barrels a day the current cap stands at 185 
million barrels for the first six months of the year 
but the cartel according to analysts has been producing above 
that level in recent months 
as a result analysts say an increase of about a million barrels 
in the supply cap should keep crude prices and consumers gasoline 
prices steady 
further details of the accord were not immediately available 
it was unclear whether the agreement would span six months or be 
for a shorter period of time 
it also was not immediately known how the ministers had dealt 
with kuwaits demand for a higher production share 
the ministers opened their midyear conference on monday then 
broke up to bargain privately the talks stalled tuesday largely due 
to kuwaits demand for a much larger share of any increase in cartel 
production in the last half of the year 
other members including influential saudi arabia want the 
increase shared proportionately among all the members 
the ministers also appeared to have settled on retaining their 
benchmark price of 18 a barrel saudi arabia had recommended 
getting rid of the target price 
the cartel late last year agreed on its supply ceiling of 185 
million barrels a day for the januaryjune period well under output 
levels at that time 
cutbacks earlier in the year helped drive prices beyond the 
cartels 18 benchmark 
prices have eased a bit recently as opec has turned up its 
production but the price of a basket of crudes monitored by the 
cartel was still more than 40 percent above the level of late 
november 
on the new york mercantile exchange the contract for july 
delivery of west texas intermediate the benchmark us crude has 
been trading at more than 20 a 42gallon barrel 
the international energy agency meanwhile reported that the 
opec nations lifted their crude production by 500000 barrels a day 
in may to 21 million barrels the highest so far this year 
the agencys monthly oil market report predicted demand for the 
cartels oil would rise in the second half of the year to about 
2085 million barrels a day the agency previously estimated demand 
for the period at 204 million barrels a day 
</TEXT>
