<TEXT>
opec ministers struck a deal wednesday 
night to restrain production in order to keep bolstering oil prices 
but crude futures tumbled in us trading on indications that some 
nations would continue cheating 
the accord signed by all 13 members of the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries in the sixth day of sometimestense 
bargaining lifts opecs official production ceiling to 195 million 
barrels a day in the julydecember period from the 185 million 
barrels in effect for januaryjune 
on the new york mercantile exchange the july contract for west 
texas intermediate the benchmark us crude closed down 79 cents 
at 1967 a barrel 
opec is limiting production in an attempt to support a price of 
18 a 42gallon barrel in the last half of the year 
analysts say opec has been pumping an estimated 21 million 
barrels a day in recent weeks so the producing nations would have 
to curb output to meet the new supply level 
everybody is supposed to rein in production levels said opec 
president rilwanu lukman 
if they do analysts say crude prices and gasoline prices at the 
pump should hold steady 
at their final strategy session the ministers agreed that a 
special committee would meet in september to review the oil market 
if it is found that the demand warrants an increase in the 
ceiling then this can be raised to 20 million barrels per day or 
any other level agreed upon read a statement released by the 
ministers any adjustments would take effect oct 1 
under the accord the 1 million barrel increase in the production 
ceiling will be distributed proportionately among all members 
talks had stalled tuesday over kuwaits demand for a greater 
share of any increase in the ceiling and some kuwaiti delegates 
indicated that nation did not accept its new quota 
lukman asked about kuwaits position told a news conference 
kuwait signed the resolution 
but kuwaiti oil minister ali khalifa alsabah later told 
reporters he had made a reservation to the agreement he said he 
would give details on thursday 
a kuwaiti delegate who demanded anonymity said his government 
doesnt feel bound by the quota assigned it under the new accord 
another kuwaiti delegate who also sought anonymity said sabah 
wrote those reservations in the margin of the agreement signed by 
the ministers 
kuwait has been pumping well over its opec quota if it continues 
doing so it would add to the world supply and possibly help weaken 
prices 
the united arab emirates also has persistently produced more than 
its ceiling there was no indication whether it intended to adhere 
to its new target although a kuwaiti delegate said the uae 
verbally expressed its reservations in the closed meeting 
prices have risen from nearterm lows reached in late 1988 
partly due to opec cutbacks earlier in the year and to accidents 
that temporarily disrupted supplies in key oilproducing regions of 
the world 
the average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by opec 
exceeded the 18 a barrel reference earlier in the year and prices 
are up more than 40 percent since last november 
in its insistence on a greater share of the increase kuwait was 
pitted against influential saudi arabia the worlds largest crude 
exporters 
saudi arabias hisham nazer walked out of the opec meeting 
handinhand with sabah in an apparent attempt to signal their 
differences were patched up 
nazer said several times during the bargaining that he wanted to 
see prices rising 
kuwait however is concerned that higher prices will erode the 
cartels share of the oil market to nonopec countries analysts 
say higher prices encourage more production and more exploration by 
producers 
the ministers statement said they intend to talk to independent 
producing nations with a view to soliciting their cooperation in 
support of market stability 
some of those countries agreed earlier in the year to curtail 
their output some to help bolster prices 
under the agreement saudi arabias new quota will be 48 million 
barrels a day up from 45 million barrels 
iran and iraq will have quotas of 28 million barrels a day up 
from 26 million barrels in the januaryjune period 
other quotas for the julydecember period are algeria 733000 
barrels per day ecuador 242000 barrels gabon 175000 and 
indonesia 13 million barrels 
others included kuwait 11 million barrels libya 11 million 
barrels nigeria 14 million barrels qatar 329000 barrels 
united arab emirates 1 million barrels and venezuela 17 million 
barrels 
