an energy company has agreed to pay a 
reported 275 million to eight families who discovered in 1987 that 
their homes sat atop a toxic waste dump officials said wednesday 
the settlement was announced at a meeting attended by the 
families local officials mediators who helped construct the deal 
and representatives of colonial gas co which once dumped on the 
site 
colonial gas acknowledged its coalgasification byproducts were 
dumped decades ago where the families homes were later built 
railroad debris leather hospital bandages bottles light 
bulbs drums metal paint cans ash paint dye and rubber shoe 
scraps were among the waste dumped at the site when it was known as 
costas dump from the 1920s to 40s 
the families reported seeing blue soil and camphorlike odors in 
1987 to the state department of environmental quality engineering 
under the settlement colonial gas will buy the homes pay 
damages and finance the continuing cleanup costs at the site near 
the concord river in this city about 35 miles north of boston 
the agreement will provide each family with approximately 
250000 the parties said colonial gas reportedly also has agreed 
to pay 750000 to the deqe for the testing and fencing and cleaning 
the site 
colonial gas attorney ralph child the cleanup would not begin for 
at least a year he said the houses either will be razed 
transported to another location or left on the site during cleanup 
as a provision of the agreement the families will not be allowed 
to seek further damages for future health problems 
in a report the deqe found the site does not currently pose an 
immediate threat to the health or welfare of abutters to the 
property 
but it said the area was unsafe to live on and remedial actions 
were necessary to ensure the protection of the families and future 
users of the site 
the families whose members complained about health problems 
including headaches and asthma were reolcated together to a 
condominium complex in another town the mediation took six months 
