<TEXT>
a sewing machine company that closed its 
massachusetts plant in 1981 has been ordered to rehire the entire 
workforce and make up eight years of lost earnings for up to 190 
employees officials said wednesday 
jubilant workers hailed the decision by the national labor 
relations board as vindication of their claim that the company 
reece corp of waltham moved operations to maine and overseas to 
escape a costly union contract 
maybe this will show people that unions hang on and defend 
people were not just dues collectors said vincent c ofria 
president of the 2000member local 1596 of the united auto workers 
which represented the reece employees 
its not clear what how much total back pay might be owed the 
nlrb must hold a separate hearing to determine that 
labor lawyers said the decision did not chart new legal ground 
but appeared to mark a shift from the nlrbs decisions under former 
president reagan when the board steadily strengthened management 
rights at the expense of unions 
peter j abate reeces president and chief executive officer 
said the company would appeal the order which could cost it 
millions of dollars in court 
the exact amount of back pay remains to be determined through a 
separate nlrb hearing joel gardiner an attorney in the nlrbs 
boston office said the hearing wont be held until after the 
companys appeal 
reece a 108yearold firm that had sales of 595 million last 
year announced in april 1981 it would close the plant which made 
industrial machinery for sewing buttonholes and pockets 
approximately 190 workers were laid off and the operations were 
transferred to plants in gorham maine and leiden the netherlands 
a threemember nlrb panel issued its decision in washington on 
may 31 but it was not received by the parties until this week 
by a 21 vote the panel overturned a 1982 decision by an 
administrative law judge who had found that the company had a 
contractual right to shut the plant 
the nlrb interpreted the contract more narrowly ruling that 
neither a managementrights clause nor a paragraph covering 
severance pay eliminated the companys obligation to bargain with 
the union over the plants future 
by refusing to bargain collectively and in good faith with the 
union the company has engaged in unfair labor practices nlrb 
chairman james m stephens and board member mary miller cracraft 
wrote 
the nlrb ordered reece to make up any difference between what the 
workers have earned over the past eight years and what they would 
have earned at the plant 
workers at the reece plant earned an average of more than 9 an 
hour and many who were paid at piece rates made more than 14 an 
hour 
the company also was required to offer the waltham employees 
immediate reinstatement to their former jobs and if those jobs no 
longer exist to equivalent positions at the companys other plants 
the board said the company would have to pay the workers moving 
costs and if necessary make jobs for them by dismissing employees 
hired after the plant closing 
the nlrb did not explain why it took nearly seven years to decide 
the case however lawyers said the board has been struggling with a 
significant backlog and delays of three years or longer are common 
the dissenting board member wilford w johansen argued the uaw 
had waived its right to bargain over the plants future by agreeing 
to put the managementrights and severance pay clauses in the 
contract 
alan h shapiro a boston labor lawyer called the decision a 
good precedent from a union perspective 
it sounds like this kind of a decision in which the board is 
not willing to buy into a waiverbycontract argument is shifting 
away from the reagan years when they found waivers in everything 
shapiro said 
</TEXT>
