mai basic four inc said wednesday it had filed a 
lawsuit opposing the postponement of prime computer incs annual 
meeting where it plans to wage a proxy battle for control of the 
company 
the suit filed in delaware chancery court seeks to compel the 
natickbased computer maker to hold the meeting june 14 as 
previously scheduled 
prime announced tuesday that it would delay the meeting until 
july 26 to give its stockholders time to consider mais recent 
reduction in its hostile tender offer from 20 a share in cash to 
approximately 19 a share in a mixture of cash and securities 
mai is a tustin califbased computer company controlled by new 
york investor bennett s lebow it has been pursuing prime a maker 
of minicomputers and computeraided design equipment since november 
on june 1 mai cut its bid to 1950 in cash for about 75 percent 
of the shares on a fully diluted basis plus securities with a face 
value of 21 per share for the remaining 25 percent of primes stock 
since the securities are likely to trade at less than face value 
many analysts have valued the new offer at 18 to 19 a share 
mai also said wednesday that prime has put an additional 5 
million into a war chest to oppose mais hostile takeover bid and 
defend tin and golden parachute arrangements 
prime previously announced charges totaling 154 million for 
legal investment banking and other costs associated with fighting 
mais tender offer 
in a filing monday with the securities and exchange commission 
prime said its board authorized a 5 million letter of credit to 
cover legal costs for defending its employee protection and 
executive retention agreements 
those agreements known generically as tin and golden parachutes 
provide payments ranging from a few hundred to many thousands of 
dollars to soften the landing for ordinary workers and top 
executives who bail out of the company after a takeover 
mai has claimed the arrangements could cost the company up to 
170 million and has pledged to fight them in court 
mai charged wednesday that prime has apparently deliberately 
chosen not to publicize this new 5 million commitment 
prime spokesman joseph gavaghan declined to comment directly on 
mais statement 
prime stock closed unchanged at 1650 a share in composite 
trading wednesday on the new york stock exchange 
